==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Wheeze
<hw>Wheeze</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Wheezed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Wheezing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>whesen</ets>, AS.
<ets>hw⟦emac⟧san</ets> (cf. Icel. <ets>hv⟦ae⟧sa</ets> to hiss, Sw.
<ets>hv⟦aum⟧sa</ets>, Dan. <ets>hv⟦ae⟧se</ets>); akin to AS.
<ets>hw⟦omac⟧sta</ets> a cough, D. <ets>hoest</ets>, G.
<ets>husten</ets>, OHG. <ets>huosto</ets>, Icel. <ets>h⟦omac⟧sti</ets>,
Lith. <ets>kosti</ets> to cough, Skr. <ets>k⟦amac⟧s</ets>. ⟦root⟧43. Cf.
<er>Husky</er> hoarse.]</ety> <def>To breathe hard, and with an audible
piping or whistling sound, as persons affected with asthma.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Wheezing</xex> lungs.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wheeze</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Wheeze
<hw>Wheeze</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A piping or whistling
sound caused by difficult respiration.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Phon.)</fld> <def>An ordinary whisper exaggerated
so as to produce the hoarse sound known as the ⟦ldquo⟧stage
whisper.⟦rdquo⟧ It is a forcible whisper with some admixture of
tone.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wheezy</ent>⟦br⟧
